Setup

Load gapminder data from the package of the same name. You may need to install the package.

library(gapminder)
data(gapminder)

gapminder has information on life expectancy, GDP per capita, and population for countries every 5 years, 1952 to 2007, with countries grouped by continent:

head(gapminder)

Overview

There are a few different ways to make plots in R. The two most common methods currently are the built-in base R plotting functions and the ggplot2 package from the tidyverse. There is a third system, from a package called lattice, that you might hear of, but it isnt as widely used currently.

Here were just going to work with base R plotting functions.

You may want to ultimatley use the ggplot2 package instead. There are examples and exercises with the ggplot focused workshop.

There are also lots of specialized visualization packages that build on the basics to do particular tasks.

Visualization with Base R

A good reference, by David Gerard, is at https://dcgerard.github.io/stat234/base_r_cheatsheet.html. Theres a lot more information there. There are just a few example plots below here.

Base plotting functions are good for quick exploratory plots, but the defaults arent really publication ready. One main criticism of the built in plotting functions is that each type of plot is made in its own way with its own options.

Histogram

A histogram

hist(gapminder$lifeExp[gapminder$year==2007])

We can change the number of bins

hist(gapminder$lifeExp[gapminder$year==2007], breaks=30)

You can also change where the breaks are, and the axis limits

hist(gapminder$lifeExp[gapminder$year==2007],
     breaks=seq(37.5, 87.5, 5), # where bins break (also determines number)
     xlim=c(35, 90)) # xaxis limits

And clean up labels

hist(gapminder$lifeExp[gapminder$year==2007],
     breaks=seq(37.5, 87.5, 5), 
     xlim=c(35, 90),
     xlab="Number of Countries",
     ylab="Life Expectancy",
     main="2007 Gapminder Data")

This is a reasonable plot to look at, but we might want to see what the distribution looks like based on course or gender. This can be done, but, with base R, its definitely not a topic for a beginner workshop.

Scatterplot

Well use the gapminder data here and make a scatterplot of life expectancy and GDP per capita in 2002.

plot(x=gapminder$gdpPercap[gapminder$year==2002], 
     y=gapminder$lifeExp[gapminder$year==2002])

Looks like theres an exponential function here. Log GDP per capita.

plot(x=gapminder$gdpPercap[gapminder$year==2002], 
     y=gapminder$lifeExp[gapminder$year==2002],
     log="x")

This log argument can be found in the help page for plot.default.

Make point size a function of population. Use a formula to scale relatively to area, not diameter. Use transparency for overlapping points.

plot(x=gapminder$gdpPercap[gapminder$year==2002], 
     y=gapminder$lifeExp[gapminder$year==2002],
     log="x",
     pch=16, cex=sqrt(1e-7*gapminder$pop[gapminder$year==2007]/pi),
     col=rgb(.2, 0, .8, alpha=.3))

Save

Theres an export button in the plot window; otherwise you have to plot to a specific graphics device.

pdf("plot1.pdf", width=6, height=4)
plot(x=gapminder$gdpPercap[gapminder$year==2002], 
     y=gapminder$lifeExp[gapminder$year==2002],
     log="x")
dev.off()
